@himanshug - What is the context of the current proposal? Does it refers to aggregators that are used only in the context of queries, when querying immutable segments that are cached off-heap? Does it also cover off-heap incremental index roll-up aggregation? If it is the first then it is reasonable to  define an API for external memory allocator, if it is the second then what I am suggesting is more relevant.
Note that Oak is considered as a core contrib and not extension, and is proposed as an efficient alternative for the existing off-heap incremental index. Which brings me back to my previous question - does the current off-heap incremental index considered operational, with reasonable performance?

I think that by introducing a new writable memory aggregator we avoid backward compatibility issues, do we not?

Okay, so I've fixed this locally, but not familiar enough with the code yet to open a PR.

During compaction, we use the ingestsegmentfirehose, and it calls lookupName on the dimensionselector. 

https://github.com/apache/incubator-druid/blob/master/server/src/main/java/org/apache/druid/segment/realtime/firehose/IngestSegmentFirehose.java#L146

I noticed we were getting back 0.0 here, which is the value serialized, but it does not look at the bitmap index. I found that the doublewrappingdimensionselector does not check IsNull on the selector, but directly calls getDouble, this violates the asset in the ColumnarDoubles getDouble function. 

https://github.com/apache/incubator-druid/blob/3ae563263a23000560749071d262727d47296856/processing/src/main/java/org/apache/druid/segment/DoubleWrappingDimensionSelector.java#L44

So to fix locally, I changed:

@Nullable
  @Override
  protected String getValue()
  {
    if (extractionFn == null) {
      return String.valueOf(selector.getDouble());
    } else {
      return extractionFn.apply(selector.getDouble());
    }
  }

to first check selector.isNull() and to return null if it is, instead of calling getDouble. After this change, nulls remain null after compacting segments for doubles, I'll need to check the other types to see if they're affected too.

